      {
        "id": 2476011,
        "name": "G. Shields",
        "username": "G_Shields",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/g_shields/{size}/2529_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-09-03T08:39:24.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Yes, another fan of this domaine over here! The Fixin\u2019s are in my mind really super values for Burgundy, and the domaine stays \u2018accessible\u2019, as they say here. They have a walk-in caveau in Fixin which makes it easy to stop by and taste without getting stuck in complexity of making appointments and i really do like the wines.<br>\nI believe that 2012 was the transition year between father and Amelie and that it was from 2013 onwards that she took over full reigns of the domaine. I\u2019ve drunk a near-half case of the 2013 Fixin Crais and Clos bottlings, and they are to me very nice indeed. Maybe a touch more austere than 2012, but lovely transparency of red fruits. The Clos is probably slightly cooler and less exuberant in style than Les Crais.  My favorite Fixin wine in her line-up  though is the \u2018En Combe Roy\u2019, sitting just underneath 1er cru Arvelet. This gets some whole cluster and i find comes across as a really complete wine, with a spicy depth on top of some lovely fruit.<br>\nThanks to William for some excellent comments: had one of her fathers 2010 Gevrey Clos des Chezeaux, and this was certainly in a chunkier and more \u2018wholesome\u2019 style, but very good nonetheless, solid old-school pinot! Interesting insight on the Vosnes, RE farming and vine material. I have a few of the PCs from 2014 and 2015, lets see how they go bearing in mind also that the holdings are small and means that the % of new oak goes quite high as she only has a barrel or two so becomes trickier to manage the elevage and get the balance right\u2026</p>",
